-- Japan, China, India, Malaysia, South Korea: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-09-28T22:59:05Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-28/japan-china-india-malaysia-south-korea-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold
media briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Bank of Japan will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its
Tankan survey of business sentiment for the third quarter. A
quarterly index of sentiment at large manufacturers rose to a
reading of 7 in September, from a reading of 1 in June,
according to a Bloomberg News survey of economists.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.955 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 83.93 per dollar at 7:51 a.m. in Tokyo.  Malaysia: The government is scheduled to auction 4 billion
ringgit ($1.3 billion) of three-year Islamic bonds and 168-day
Islamic notes today. It also plans to sell 3 billion ringgit of
210- and 364-day notes.  The yield on the 3.835 percent bond due August 2015 was
3.26 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0888.  India: The government plans to raise as much as 35 billion
rupees ($776 million) by selling treasury bills today. It will
offer 20 billion rupees of 91-day securities and 15 billion
rupees of 182-day notes, according to the central bank.  The yield on the 7.84 percent bond due in May 2020 was 7.94
percent. The rupee was at 45.1575.  China: Markit will unveil China’s HSBC China Services PMI
for September. The gauge was at 51.9 in August. The yield on the
2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was 2.649 percent. The yuan
was at 6.6906.  South Korea: The ministry of Finance and Strategy will
unveil current-account data for August. The country had a
surplus of $5.88 billion in July.  The yield on the 3.75 percent note due in June 2013 was
3.38 percent. The won was at 1,146.25 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Andrea Wong  in Hong Kong at 
